Thought I'd share my current shelf situation  the lighting can be pretty poor in my place so I did what I could.  The first image is in my second bedroom with most of the collection  PS1  PS2  PSP  Vita  Gamecube  Wii  Wii U  DS  3DS and the Game Boy line. There's a few figures around as well as some rad gifts and sentimental things  I have plenty more of them but can't display them all. If you can see I have games from all over the globe  I don't really care what region a game comes from as long as I can play it in some fashion and it's physical. Instgram sure does compress the shit out of images though.  The second image is in my living area  PS4  PS3 and Switch  the collections I tend to give the most attention and play time currently. There's another 2 rows of PS3 cut off and the shelf next to it is my anime as well as movies and TV shows that my partner and I own. I was suprised the other day to see on my game collecting app that I hit 160 PS4 games... what a crazy console with so many games that are fantastic. Still many I need to play as I sure as hell haven't played eveything I own. Across all consoles  I'd say I've played somewhere between 80-85% of games  and finished another 80% of those. The rest  I got my time in and I'm satisfied. To want to finish everything is a fool's errand. Salah satu game indie milik Xbox Game Studios telah dirilis untuk port Nintendo Switch  mengingat Nintendo dan Microsoft memiliki hubungan baik dalam bentuk kerja sama di dalam mengembangkan industri game dunia. Barcode scanning toys and arcade games were extremely popular in the 90's Japan including the Datach Famicom add on  the later Digivices and Barcode Wars by Bandai. The strength of the Barcode Wars series was its connection to nintendo  allowing them to make exclusive barcode games with nintendo franchise such as Mario Bros and Zelda. . Did you go to the eshop and download yourself a copy of Gold Silver or Crystal?  Only getting the Red Gyradose as your first shiny? And want more?  What if i told you that in Gen 2 you can breed a shiny with a non shiny Pokemon Turning your odds from 1/8192 to 1/64 through breeding? --- Shiny hunting feels impossible through gen 2 and onward to some of us because of how high the odds are and theres no shiny charm till black and white 2.  Well In gen 2 theres something in the coding that makes Breeding a shiny with a mon shiny pop out shinies a bit faster  I believe its only breeding males with females of the same species or egg group  Anyway.  So you may not have a shiny ditto yet  Theres two ways to get one Random encounter one Or Use your red gyradose to trade to red blue or yellow use on a ditto only with mimic then catch and trade back to gsc  If you just have the Shiny Gyradose what can you breed with it?  One example is Dragonair  Another Tentacruel  A helpful thing to know is your egg groups  Gyradose is in the Water 2 and dragon egg group Dragonair is in the Dragon egg group Ekans is in the field and dragon egg group Tentacruel is in the water 2 egg group Ekans can breed with any field egg group mon such as mankey and primeape even eevee  I have done this shiny hunt method myself Getting myself various Shiny Pokemon  Since theres no abilities eggs will hatch relatively slow  Some hatch faster than others such as Magikarp hatching faster than lapras or snorlax  So my suggestion is trying magikarp first test your patience Then try Dratini or Something else.  If you're like "woah shit is this true?" I finally beat the game!!!!! (Golden Deer  Maddening)  It was extremely tough but I really enjoyed the story and gameplay. Lysethia was indeed my best unit throughout the whole game.  With her staff Thyrsus and couple of buff abilities  she became the most reliable glass cannon in my team.  Not to mention that she cleared nearly half of the units in the final mission.  Here is my regular roster for this level Hilda - Great Knight Berna - Bow Knight Dorothea - Gremory Ingrid - Falcon Knight Lysethia - Dark Knight Marianne - Holy Knight Mercedes - Bishop Petra - Assasin Annette - Gremory Claude - Barbossa Byleth - Enlightened One  Yes it was an all-star harem team paradise lol  I think attack range and mobility are most important in this game. I really spammed Lysethia's 'sniping' which helped me clear missions in a breeze. I even gave her all the magic boosting items so that she can become a hyper-carry mage.  I love this game and cannot wait to play a more harder level of this one. Hope there are some more side stories in the DLC!  #fireemblem #fireemblemthreehouses #nintendoswitch #nintendo #lysethia

Ever pick up a used copy of  Black  white  black 2 and white 2 and ever look at them like "Man i wish i could get the old event mons/items"  Well...what if i told you that In 2019 (2020) you can access them. This can be preformed with a 3ds family system and can also work for the original ds family line (not dsi line) ------ Without further adu gen 5. How to preform the trick: Step one: Go into your Wi-Fi settings  Step 2. Change the dns settings on your primary Wi-Fi connection Only the primary settings and insert these numbers 164.132.44.106.¬† Then hit okay and you're done! ---- You can preform this trick with gen 4 but it requires alot more effort that is difficult for me to explain so i have provided a link in my bio for how to do gen 4. ---- What mystery gifts can you get for gen 5?  Well....the mythicals for that gen. These events can be transfered up to gen 7 through pokebank. Review Summary- Control ===================== SCORE: 9.1 ===================== You looking for a paranormal  sci-fi action game? This is the game for you! I can guarantee you haven't played anything quite like this before.  It has such a unique style and atmosphere  it oozes mystique  and has a certain stillness that keeps you on edge. It's reminiscent of the old Stanley Kubrick classics  so it wouldn't surprise me if that's where they got their inspiration from.  The combat is some of the most fun you'll have this year. Both the gunplay and psychic abilities are polished and each battle is a thrill. You'll always leave the battlefield in a state of choas  thanks to the destructible environments.  The story is full of mystery and will keep you invested  even if it can be a bit confusing at times  especially with the in-game terminology. Extra lore is told through an excessive amount of collectibles  so while there is a lot to learn about this fascinating world  you're constantly stopping to read yet again. It disrupts gameplay and I do wish it was handled more efficiently.  The side missions are just as much of a standout as the main story  with each one containing an interesting and unique storyline  and I always looked forward to each one.  Exploration was one of the weaker elements of the game  as it did get a little frustrating at times getting to where you needed to go. But this was made up by the amount of hidden secrets (and even some good puzzles) scattered around each area.  While it's a relatively short game  I still recommend this to anyone  as it's one of the better games this year. On-going review- Control ==================== My last post before I wrap up my review tomorrow. Now I've been mostly positive about this game so far  but it's not perfect  and there were a couple of things that held it back from true greatness.  I already talked about the excessive amounts of collectibles in my last post. It's fine to have a lot of extra lore  but surely there was a more efficient way to go about it.  My other main issue was how useless the map was. Maybe use it as a rough guide  but not to go exactly where you need to go. A lot of areas are multi-story  and the map just shows everything in one clump. If you're trying to get from one room to another  the map be more misleading than anything  and I did get frustrated quite a few times trying to get around.  When you think of maps from other games  like Resident Evil 2  they're laid out so clearly it helps makes exploration more fun because you're not wasting time looking at blank walls where the map says there should a doorway.  But I will admit my criticisms are fairly minor and didn't detract too much from the fun overall. True Rare Rating - 9.2  Limited Edition GameStop Managers Yoshi's Island DS Sweepstakes Statue. Production numbers unknown but very likely under 50 made.  In November 2006 Yoshi's Island DS was released. To reward the GameStop managers who had the most pre-orders there was a questionnaire sent out to each store that reached a specific number of pre-order sales. if the questionnaire was filled out and sent back to corporate that particular manager was put into a sweepstakes drawing for this awesome Yoshi's Island Statue.  The winners did not get them until late the following year and many of the managers who won were no longer employed for the company üòÇ Those that did get them and were still around found that their shipment was commonly broken.  There have only been a dozen or so seen circulating  and many of them were broken during reshipment. This is very much a dwindling supply asset due to fragility. Level-5 has changed the title of the Inazuma Eleven Ares game to Inazuma Eleven: Great Road of Heroes and announced a spring 2020 release window for Japan. . In a blog post  Level-5 apologized for the miscalculations that have occurred in development thus far  which resulted in the Inazuma Eleven Ares anime series and its sequel Inazuma Eleven: Orion no Kokuin to conclude before the release of the game. However  development of the game has since moved from an outsourced to a fully in-house development system  which has allowed further system revisions to create a game with more exciting battles. . Inazuma Eleven: Great Road of Heroes is based on the drama of Inazuma Eleven Ares and features additional episodes in which past characters also appear. . Like previous Inazuma Eleven titles  the game system will offer a high level of freedom in which player positions are indicated by the controller (or mouse). It promises to be a completely new type of RPG that incorporates eSports developments  as well as enhanced hack-and-slash elements such as battles and player gatherings. Level-5 also hopes to make a deep online system with a wide range of tactics in whch national tournaments can be held. . Inazuma Eleven: Great Road of Heroes is in development for PlayStation 4  Switch  iOS  and Android. . #InazumaElevenGreatRoadOfHeroes #level5 #InazumaElevenAres #football #soccer #anime #animation #manga #playstation4 #playstation #ps4 #switch #nintendo #nintendoswitch #ios #android #smartphone #vg4n_InazumaElevenGreatRoadOfHeroes . Does anyone else Remember Minecade? Well  if you don't  then I can't say I blame you. Minecade was a server network that was popular in the Java edition of Minecraft for a short while. One of the most popular games on it was Super Craft Bross  which was basically Kit PVP with double jumping and special abilities. Sethbling  a Minecraft YouTuber who specializes in making mechanics and contraptions  was a pretty big face of the server for a while.  However  as time went by  things around the server started to go downhill. Updates for Super Craft Bros. were few and far between. Balancing issues and bugs were rarely if ever  fixed. To make things worse  Minecraft's popularity was in a lull. It was around this time I quit playing on Minecade because the games I liked just weren't fun to play anymore.  Fast forward to now. With Minecraft getting a bit of an extra life when it comes to mainstream popularity  I wondered what Minecade has been up to. Last I checked  they could barely break 50 players  and those players were mostly on a rather basic creative server. When I went to the website  all I found was  well  this. The website is a mess. I‚Äôve also checked around a few forums and can‚Äôt find much.  So. What happened to Minecade? I‚Äôve been steadily picking at 'Fire Emblem Three Houses' for the past month or so and while I admit I haven‚Äôt quite finished the game I can say confidently that it is one of my favorites of the year. While I don‚Äôt have a ton of experience with the Fire Emblem series it's hard to imagine the diehards finding too much at fault with it‚Äôs core gameplay. The turn based ‚Äúrock paper scissors‚Äù battles the series is iconic for are so engaging and addictive to play and beautifully presented. There‚Äôs something so epic about having the camera rapidly zoom in to the ground level of the battlefield so you can watch your characters duke it out. But I think the crowning achievement of this game is its story and narrative structure. You play as ‚ÄúThe Professor‚Äù a sort of blank slate character who finds him or herself teaching at a prestigious military academy. In between battles you will fill your time lecturing and getting to know your students (who of course are your soldiers in battles) all the while completing side quests around the school. It‚Äôs essentially a lighter but more focused version of what the Persona series does. Within the first couple hours of play I found myself really caring for my students and motivated to prepare them as effectively as I could so they wouldn‚Äôt die in combat (yes perma-death is still a thing if you want it). This along with a storyline that evolves and twists based on your actions and choices makes for an immensely satisfying narrative experience. Barcode scanning toys and arcade games were extremely popular in the 90's Japan including the Datach Famicom add on  the later Digivices and Barcode Wars by Bandai. The strength of the Barcode Wars series was its connection to nintendo  allowing them to make exclusive barcode games with nintendo franchise such as Mario Bros and Zelda. . It also allowed players connect to their Super Famicom or original Gameboy via the 'Barcode Boy' to send data from the barcode cards into the Barcode Battler console games. . Barcode Battler was highly successful in Japan and even saw a release of western versions with alternative art and characters. .
